The short answer is, I think, no. The connection handle (the thing you get out of the _Connection Complete_ event) doesn't ever come out of the internals of the AF_BLUETOOTH socket, as far as I can tell. 

@gonzob - you're getting the connection handle by looking at hcidump output, or something??

It's looking increasingly like I'm going to give up on BlueZ and write a whole stack just in Python, talking to a raw HCI socket.

@newville https://wiki.python.org/moin/GlobalInterpreterLock That's the reason you cannot run CPU intensive threads (meaning your main thread will stop even if you run asteval in thread as you suggested in comment https://github.com/newville/asteval/issues/3#issuecomment-9764184). Any asteval code ran in thread won't react to main thread commands, pipes will be locked and main thread won't run at all. Your program will just halt with 100% CPU usage.

I just corrected you that the only way around this in CPython is not threads but multiprocessing, then even if forked child is running 100% cpu usage - you have OS level control over it and can just send signal to SIGKILL it on timeout (exactly my first comment).

So while @voidfiles closed this ticket moving on to javascript nodejs I simply suggested similar workaround with forking instead of threading. CPython threads are not real threads, because they still share GIL.

