Below is the (hacky) solution I came up with for django-cities-light:

```
class LazyProgressBar(progressbar.ProgressBar):
    """
    Less CPU-intensive progressbar with lazy update.

    Performs update() only if value increment is large enough to add more bars
    to progressbar according to current terminal width.
    """
    def update(self, value=None):
        if None not in (value, self.previous_value):
            if self.max_value is not progressbar.base.UnknownLength:
                divisor = self.max_value // self.term_width or 1
                if (value - self.previous_value) // divisor == 0:
                    return
        super(LazyProgressBar, self).update(value=value)
```

If you're using the admin integration, then the registration will be done automatically to follow the inlines. No need to manually call reversion.register!

However, if you want to do it manually, what you want is:

``` py
@reversion.register(follow=['b_set'])
class A(models.Model):
    pass

@reversion.register(follow="a")
class B(models.Model):
    a = models.ForeignKey(A)
```

That is, you specify the name of the attribute on the model that represents the relationship.

