So I've had a quick go at this problem.  Created a class that keeps track of a timestamp in microseconds, with an estimate() method that attempts to estimate the flight controller time based on the last known time plus the time elapsed from the companion computer clock.
```
# Define tracking timer class
class TrackTimer:
    def __init__(self):
        self.fctimeus = None
        self.delta = None
        self.debug = False
    def update(self, timeus):
        if self.debug:
            print "Expected timeus: " +str(self.estimate()) +", actual timeus: " +str(timeus)
        # Messages come in or are processed asynchronously, out of order, so a later message may have an earlier timestamp.
        # So ignore any updates that are older than what we already know about
        if timeus > self.fctimeus:
            self.fctimeus = timeus
            self.mytimeus = datetime.now()
    def actual(self):
        return self.fctimeus
    def estimate(self):
        if self.fctimeus:
            self.delta = datetime.now() - self.mytimeus
            return int(self.fctimeus + (self.delta.total_seconds() * 1000))
        else:
            return None
```

You can then use a decorator/listener to try and grab timestamps from all incoming messages:
```
# Create a new tracktimer object to try and keep sync with the flight controller
trackfctime = TrackTimer()
# Setup a listener for all incoming mavlink messages and update our time tracker whenever possible
@vehicle.on_message("*")
def listener_all(self, name, message):
    try:
        trackfctime.update(message.time_usec)
    except:
        pass
    try:
        trackfctime.update(message.time_boot_ms * 1000)
    except:
        pass
```

At any time you can get an estimate:
```
print trackfctime.estimate()
```
Or the last known time:
```
print trackfctime.actual()
```

It looks like the listener often processes or returns messages out of order, so returns a message that has an older timestamp than a previously processed message.  So the class above ignores anything older than it already knows about, but this may not always be desirable behaviour.  I'm sure this can be refined better by others.

